SIMPLE: formed
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Formed
<hw>Formed</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocir⟧rmd)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>Arranged, as stars in a constellation; <as>as,
<ex>formed</ex> stars</as>.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Having structure; capable of
growth and development; organized; <as>as, the <ex>formed</ex> or
organized ferments</as>. See <er>Ferment</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Formed material</b></col> <fld>(Biol.)</fld>, <cd>a term
employed by Beale to denote the lifeless matter of a cell, that which is
physiologically dead, in distinction from the truly germinal or living
matter.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Formedon</ent>⟦br⟧
